This paper discusses a security mechanism for web browsers, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. The paper also proposes a policy mechanism for web developers, which could fall under the cs.SE (Software Engineering) sub-category. The use of JavaScript programming language and native APIs suggests that it could also belong to the cs.PL (Programming Languages) sub-category. The evaluation of performance overheads and testing of examples could indicate a focus on cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) or cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-categories.
